Introduction

Data Description

The data set analyzed can be obtained from the Kaggle platform. It’s part of the “Global YouTube Statistics 2023” challenge. https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/nelgiriyewithana/global-youtube-statistics-2023

YouTube.com is a video-sharing platform that allows users to upload, watch, and interact with videos from all over the world.The Global YouTube Statistics 2023 dataset is a collection of data about YouTube channels, videos, and their respective view counts. The data set spans from January 2023 to March 2023, and includes information about the channel’s name, country, subscriber count, video title, view count, and category.

Data Sources

Understanding the socio-economic context in which YouTube channels thrive is vital for comprehending their patterns and trends. Thus, this analysis incorporates additional data from the World Bank to assess the impact of Gross Domestic Product (GDP) per capita and other socio-economic factors on YouTube channel creation and performance[5]. The choice to include data from 2005 to 2022 was motivated by the fact that YouTube was established in 2005, and analyzing the years following its launch provides insights into the platform’s evolution and the growth of YouTube content creators.

Data preprocessing is a crucial step in ensuring that the dataset is in a suitable format for analysis. Missing data can significantly impact the accuracy of the analysis. To address this issue, the CSV file “youtube_UTF_8.csv” was read into R, with careful consideration given to the presence of missing values represented by the string “nan”. Using the na.strings argument in the read.csv function, these “nan” entries were transformed into standard missing value representations (NA) in R, enhancing the data’s consistency and analytical potential.

To better understand the socio-economic context surrounding YouTube channel creation and performance, the World Bank data was integrated into the analysis. Only the relevant columns (i.e., “Country Name” and “Code”) were retained, alongside a newly calculated variable, “Average GDP per Capita.” The latter was computed as the mean of GDP per capita values from 2005 to 2022. Merging this World Bank data with the original dataset using “Country” as the key variable enabled the study to consider how economic factors could influence YouTube channel-related phenomena.

The “channel_age” variable was introduced, allowing us to gauge the duration of YouTube channels’ existence. This age calculation was based on the most recent date found in the dataset and each channel’s creation date. In cases where the creation date was missing or mislabeled as “1970-01-01,” these entries were corrected to NA to maintain data integrity.

The adoption of this data-driven approach, coupled with data preprocessing techniques, aims to set the stage for a comprehensive analysis of YouTube channel performance and longevity in the context of socio-economic factors.

Choosing the response (target) variable

The response variable for our classification task was chosen as the dichotomy between “old” and “new” channels. This demarcation was established by utilizing February 14, 2012, as a reference date. On this date, YouTube introduced its Partner Program, a significant milestone in the platform’s history. It marked the moment when content creators were provided with opportunities for monetization[6]. This distinct transition in the platform’s evolution serves as an effective reference point, dividing channels into “old” (predating the Partner Program) and “new” (created after its introduction). To reflect this distinction in the dataset, we assigned the value -1 to “old” channels and 1 to “new” channels.

Data Cleaning

Missing data is a common issue in real-world datasets, and addressing it is paramount to avoid biased or misleading results. In our dataset, missing values were strategically handled in categorical columns. To facilitate this process, a custom function, “add_missing,” was devised and applied to each categorical column.

Ensuring data consistency and clarity is a fundamental aspect of data cleaning. In our dataset, certain column names were modified to enhance consistency and prevent future mismatches. Specifically, columns were renamed to align with their original column names, safeguarding the integrity of our dataset.

Categorical and numerical columns are distinct data types, and treating them differently is pivotal in the modeling process. For this reason, we separated the names of these two types of columns for targeted data preprocessing. This segregation aids in maintaining the structural integrity of the dataset while enabling focused operations on each data type.

Numerical columns with missing values required specific treatment. We employed a missingness treatment strategy to impute the missing data. This method ensures that the integrity of the numerical data is preserved, which is crucial for subsequent analyses

The treated categorical and numerical columns were consolidated into a single prepared data frame labeled “d.” To maintain continuity, the response variable “oldNew” was reintegrated into this dataset.

add_missing <- function(column_old) {
  column_new <- column_old
  levels(column_new) <- c(levels(column_old), "Missing")
  for (i in 1:length(column_new)) {
  if (is.na(column_new[i])) {
    column_new[i] <- "Missing"
  }
  }
  column_new
}

Data Splitting

We begin by setting a random seed (in this case, 729375) to ensure the reproducibility of our results. Then, a random grouping variable, “rgroup,” is created to facilitate data splitting. The “rgroup” variable is filled with random uniform values, ensuring that approximately 90% of the data is allocated to the training set, and the remaining 10% is designated for the validation (or calibration) set.

Once the data is split, a distinction is made between categorical and numerical features. Categorical variables, including those initially labeled as “factor” or “character,” are grouped as “catVars.” Similarly, numerical variables, including those of “numeric” or “integer” type, are grouped as “numericVars.”

set.seed(729375)
d$rgroup <- runif(nrow(d))
dTrainAll <- subset(d, rgroup<=0.9)
dTest <- subset(d, rgroup > 0.9)

vars <- setdiff(colnames(dTrainAll), c(outcome,'rgroup'))

catVars <- vars[sapply(dTrainAll[,vars], class) %in% c('factor','character')]
numericVars <- vars[sapply(dTrainAll[,vars], class) %in% c('numeric','integer')]
# split dTrainAll into a training set and a validation (or calibration) set
useForCal <- rbinom(n=dim(dTrainAll)[[1]], size=1, prob=0.1) > 0
dCal <- subset(dTrainAll, useForCal)
dTrain <- subset(dTrainAll,!useForCal)

Data partitioning is a fundamental practice in machine learning, ensuring that our models are tested on unseen data to assess their generalizability. This process begins with splitting the training data, “dTrainAll,” into two segments: a training set (“dTrain”) and a validation (or calibration) set (“dCal”). The split is strategically conducted, employing a binomial distribution to randomly assign a portion of the data to the calibration set.

The division helps us develop and refine our models on one subset of the data, while simultaneously validating and tuning them on another. It also mitigates the risk of overfitting, which occurs when models are excessively tailored to the training data and fail to perform well on new, unseen data.

This feature selection and data splitting phase is crucial for the subsequent building and evaluation of classification models. The process ensures that we use the most informative features and employ an effective model validation strategy. The results obtained from these steps will be discussed in the forthcoming sections of our project.

Single Variable Models

We applied the mkPredC function to all categorical variables. This function performs single variable prediction for a given categorical column. It calculates the probability of a positive outcome based on the proportion of positive outcomes for each level in the column. The function also accounts for missing values, ensuring they are handled appropriately during the calculation.

For numerical variables, we transformed them into categorical variables using quantiles and the cut function. The mkPredN function was then applied, which internally uses the mkPredC function for these categorical representations of numerical data.

# perform single variable prediction for a given categorical column
mkPredC <- function(outCol, varCol, appCol) {
  pPos <- sum(outCol == pos,na.rm = TRUE) / length(outCol)
  naTab <- table(as.factor(outCol[is.na(varCol)]),useNA = 'ifany')
  pPosWna <- (naTab/sum(naTab))[pos]
  vTab <- table(as.factor(outCol), varCol)
  pPosWv <- (vTab[pos, ] + 1.0e-3*pPos) / (colSums(vTab) + 1.0e-3)
  pred <- pPosWv[appCol]
  pred[is.na(appCol)] <- pPosWna
  pred[is.na(pred)] <- pPos
  pred
}

mkPredN <- function(outCol, varCol, appCol) {
  cuts <- unique(as.numeric(
    quantile(varCol, probs=seq(0, 1, 0.1), na.rm=T)))
  varC <- cut(varCol, cuts)
  appC <- cut(appCol, cuts)
  mkPredC(outCol, varC, appC)
}

for (v in catVars) {

The results of the AUC analysis will be used to inform the selection of variables for the subsequent stages of the classification process. They will also serve as a guide for the development of more complex models in the later sections of our analysis.

calcAUC <- function(predcol,outcol) {
  perf <- performance(prediction(predcol,outcol==pos),'auc')
  as.numeric(perf@y.values)
}


# Create an empty data frame to store AUC values

We selected a set of variables, encompassing both categorical and numerical ones, to examine their performance using the cross-validation process. For each variable, we performed 100 repetitions of cross-validation, ensuring comprehensive coverage. In each repetition, we randomly split the data into two subsets: one for training and the other for calibration. This randomization technique allowed us to gauge the variability in model performance.

A critical performance metric, the Area Under the Curve (AUC), was computed for each repetition. This metric provided insights into the predictive power of each variable. Specifically, we calculated the mean and standard deviation of the AUC values across the 100 repetitions. These statistics offer valuable information about the consistency and reliability of the single-variable models.

By conducting this rigorous cross-validation analysis, we ensured that the selected variables have stable predictive power across different data subsets. The resulting metrics will guide us in choosing the most reliable variables for our classification models and help in making informed decisions in the subsequent sections of our analysis.

We conducted feature selection using log likelihood as the criterion to assess the performance of individual variables in our classification model. The primary objective was to identify the top-performing variables among both categorical and numerical features.

To begin, we calculated the log likelihood of the Null model on the calibration set (dCal). The log likelihood serves as a measure of how well the model fits the data. A lower log likelihood indicates a weaker fit to the data.

We then evaluated the categorical variables to determine their contributions to the model’s deviance reduction compared to the Null model. If the deviance reduction was greater than a specified threshold (minDrop), we considered the variable as a top-performing categorical variable. Similarly, we assessed the numerical variables for their deviance reduction, following the same criteria. The selected categorical and numerical variables were stored in selCatVars and selNumVars, respectively.

The top-performing single variables, represented by the selected variables, were evaluated using the Area Under the Curve (AUC) on the test set (dTest). The AUC is a common metric used to assess the predictive power of models, with higher values indicating better performance.

# Define a function to compute log likelihood so that we can reuse it.
logLikelihood <- function(ypred, ytrue,epsilon=1e-6) {
  sum(ifelse(ytrue, log(ypred+epsilon), log(1-ypred-epsilon)), na.rm=T)
}
# Compute the likelihood of the Null model on the calibration
logNull <- logLikelihood(sum(dCal[,outcome]==pos)/nrow(dCal), dCal[,outcome]==pos)

cat("The log likelihood of the Null model is:", logNull)

Multi-variate models

Decision Trees

Model 1: AUC-Based Feature Selection

we employed AUC-based feature selection, choosing four variables: Population, Average_GDP_PCAP, category, and channel_type. The resulting model exhibited a strong performance across training, calibration, and test datasets. On the training data, it achieved an AUC of 0.745, showcasing its ability to differentiate between channel outcomes. Similarly, the model displayed solid predictive power on the calibration dataset (AUC = 0.721) and maintained reasonable performance when tested on new data (AUC = 0.680). This model provides a promising foundation for multi-variable classification, thanks to its robust feature selection method.

Model 2: Log Likelihood-Based Feature Selection

In contrast, dt2 was created through log-likelihood-based feature selection, utilizing five variables: channel_type, subscribers, Population, Average_GDP_PCAP, and country_rank. Next we conducted a comprehensive evaluation of two decision tree models with different feature selection methods. The performance of these models was assessed using key metrics, including accuracy, precision, recall, F1 score, and normalized deviance. The goal was to determine which model performs better in predicting the “oldNew” outcome variable.

performanceMeasures <- function(ytrue, ypred, model.name = "model") {
   # compute the normalised deviance
   dev.norm <- -2 * logLikelihood(ytrue, ypred)/length(ypred)
   # compute the confusion matrix
   cmat <- table(actual = ytrue, predicted = ypred)
   accuracy <- sum(diag(cmat)) / sum(cmat)
   precision <- cmat[2, 2] / sum(cmat[, 2])
   recall <- cmat[2, 2] / sum(cmat[2, ])
   f1 <- 2 * precision * recall / (precision + recall)
   data.frame(model = model.name, precision = precision,
              recall = recall, f1 = f1, dev.norm = dev.norm)
}


panderOpt <- function(){
  # setting up Pander Options
  panderOptions("plain.ascii", TRUE)
  panderOptions("keep.trailing.zeros", TRUE)
  panderOptions("table.style", "simple")
  
}

pretty_perf_table <- function(model, xtrain, ytrain,
                              xtest, ytest, threshold=0.5) {
   # Option setting for Pander  
   panderOpt()
   perf_justify <- "lrrrr" 

   # call the predict() function to do the predictions
   pred_train <- predict(model, newdata=xtrain)
   pred_test <- predict(model, newdata=xtest)

   # comparing performance on training vs. test
   trainperf_df <- performanceMeasures(
      ytrain, pred_train >= threshold, model.name="training")
   testperf_df <- performanceMeasures(
      ytest, pred_test >= threshold, model.name="test")

   # combine the two performance data frames using rbind()
   perftable <- rbind(trainperf_df, testperf_df)
   pandoc.table(perftable, justify = perf_justify)
}

    roc_2 <- rocit(score=predcol2, class=outcol2==pos)
    plot(roc_1, col = c("blue","green"), lwd = 3,
      legend = FALSE,YIndex = FALSE, values = TRUE, asp=1)
    lines(roc_2$TPR ~ roc_2$FPR, lwd = 3, 
          col = c("red","green"), asp=1)
    legend("bottomright", col = c("blue","red", "green"),
       c("Test Data", "Training Data", "Null Model"), lwd = 2)
}

The fundamental concept behind SVM is to find a hyperplane that best separates different classes within your dataset. This hyperplane can be thought of as a decision boundary that maximizes the margin between the classes, making it an effective tool for classification.

In the context of our project, where we use four variables as predictors, the SVM model aims to find the ideal three-dimensional hyperplane in a 3D space. This hyperplane effectively divides the data into distinct classes, allowing for accurate classification.

Hyperparameter Tuning for SVM

To optimize the SVM model for our dataset, we manually carried out several hyperparameter tuning tasks. These tasks involved adjusting critical parameters such as the type of SVM model (linear or radial) and the cost parameter, which penalizes the model for misclassifications. Fine-tuning these hyperparameters is crucial to strike the right balance between memorization and generalization.

Penalizing the model for misclassifications ensures that it learns the data effectively, but not to the extent of rote memorization. This trade-off is demonstrated by the increasing Area Under the Curve (AUC) metric, which measures model performance, with higher penalties. A small increase in AUC (around 5%) can indicate a more stringent but appropriately generalizing model.

Unscaled ROC Plots

In our analysis, we also generated ROC (Receiver Operating Characteristic) plots for the numerical variables. These plots are created without scaling the probabilities, providing a visualization of the model’s performance. ROC plots are essential for understanding how well the SVM model discriminates between different classes.

These components of our SVM analysis shed light on the importance of hyperparameter tuning and the performance characteristics of our classification model, ultimately contributing to the development of an accurate and efficient predictive tool.

Evaluating SVM Performance with ROC Curves

To comprehensively assess the performance of our Support Vector Machine (SVM) model created with Feature Subset 1, we relied on ROC (Receiver Operating Characteristic) curves. ROC curves are valuable tools for understanding a model’s ability to discriminate between classes by analyzing its sensitivity and specificity across various thresholds. Our custom function, plot_svm_roc2, was utilized for this purpose. This function contrasts the SVM model’s performance on both the training and testing datasets with a Null Model. The Null Model is a baseline model, often described as the worst-case scenario. It predicts class labels based on the overall class distribution, without considering any features.

plot_svm_roc2 <- function(svm_model, train_data, test_data) {
  
  # Train the Null Model on the training data
  null_model <- glm(oldNew ~ 1, data = train_data, family = "binomial")
  
  # Make predictions on the training data for the SVM model and Null Model
  svm_pred_train <- predict(svm_model, newdata = train_data)
  null_pred_train <- predict(null_model, newdata = train_data, type = "response")
  
  # Calculate the ROC curves for the SVM model and Null Model on the training data
  svm_roc_train <- roc(train_data$oldNew, as.numeric(svm_pred_train))
  null_roc_train <- roc(train_data$oldNew, as.numeric(null_pred_train))
  
  # Make predictions on the test data for the SVM model and Null Model
  svm_pred_test <- predict(svm_model, newdata = test_data)
  null_pred_test <- predict(null_model, newdata = test_data, type = "response")
  
  # Calculate the ROC curves for the SVM model and Null Model on the test data
  svm_roc_test <- roc(test_data$oldNew, as.numeric(svm_pred_test))
  null_roc_test <- roc(test_data$oldNew, as.numeric(null_pred_test))
  
  # Plot the ROC curves for the SVM model, Null Model
  ggplot() +
    geom_line(aes(x = svm_roc_train$specificities, y = svm_roc_train$sensitivities, color = "Training"), linetype = "solid") +
    geom_line(aes(x = svm_roc_test$specificities, y = svm_roc_test$sensitivities, color = "Testing"), linetype = "solid") +
    geom_line(aes(x = null_roc_train$specificities, y = null_roc_train$sensitivities, color = "Null Model"), linetype = "dashed") +
    labs(x = "False Positive Rate", y = "True Positive Rate", title = "ROC Curves for Training, Testing and Null Model", legend="Model Legend", color="Model Legend") +
    scale_x_reverse() +
    scale_color_manual(values = c("Training" = "blue", "Testing" = "red", "Null Model" = "black")) +
    theme_bw()
}

Clustering

Clustering helps reveal hidden patterns within the dataset that might not be immediately evident. As we are dealing with records representing YouTube channels, we aim to identify distinct groups of channels that offer unique insights within the context of our data.

To initiate the clustering process, we take an important step in data preprocessing by scaling our dataset. Scaling ensures that the data has a mean of 0 and a standard deviation of 1, which is a standard practice for many clustering algorithms. To do this, we select a subset of relevant numerical variables to use in the clustering process, avoiding highly correlated variables to prevent overburdening the model.

We store these selected variables in the ‘vars.to.use’ variable and apply the ‘scale()’ function to the dataset, achieving the desired scaling. Subsequently, we display the centroids (the mean values) of the scaled variables, offering insights into the distribution of these features after scaling.

vars.to.use <- c("subscribers","video_views","uploads","country_rank", "channel_type_rank", "highest_monthly_earnings","Average_GDP_PCAP")
scaled_df <- scale(d[ ,vars.to.use])
attr(scaled_df, "scaled:center")

Scaling the data is essential for clustering because it standardizes the variables, ensuring that they are on a common scale. This step is crucial for various clustering algorithms. By selecting meaningful and uncorrelated variables for clustering, we streamline the process and make it more effective. Overloading the model with redundant information can lead to less interpretable clusters. Centroids represent the center of each variable’s distribution. These values provide a reference point for understanding the distribution of the scaled features. In this case, we see how subscribers, video views, uploads, and other attributes vary around their mean values after scaling.

We can observe the successful standardization of the variables. As intended, the mean of all variables is precisely 0, indicating that the data has been effectively centered. To achieve this, the records have been automatically shifted into the negative domain while preserving their relative differences.

The mean of 0 across all variables is a result of the successful scaling process. This is crucial for clustering algorithms that rely on consistent scales for accurate results. The distribution of the scaled variables now has a standard deviation of 1, making it suitable for various clustering techniques. Each variable’s minimum and maximum values show how the data points are distributed within that variable’s range after scaling, providing insights into their relative magnitudes.

The variance is also printed below for each column

attr(scaled_df, "scaled:scale")

The variance in each column, which is indicative of the spread or dispersion of data points within that specific variable, has been successfully standardized as well. The standard deviations for each variable are now quite similar, with values ranging from approximately 3,424 to 14,144,830. This standardization ensures that all variables are on the same scale and contributes to an effective clustering process.

Manhattan distance, a distance metric chosen for our clustering process, is a suitable measure for calculating distances between data points. This metric quantifies the distance between two points as the sum of the absolute differences of their coordinates, making it a robust choice for our clustering goals. We opted for this metric after experimenting with various distance measures, as it proved effective in mitigating cluster overlap.

dist <- dist(scaled_df, method="manhattan")

Hierarchical clustering, in conjunction with Ward’s method, has been selected as the clustering technique for our analysis. Ward’s method is particularly advantageous because it minimizes variances between points within a cluster. This approach works well for our dataset by identifying natural groupings that minimize the variability within each cluster.

pfit <- hclust(dist, method="ward.D2") # perform hierarchical clustering

In the visualization step, a dendrogram has been plotted based on the hierarchical clustering results. The dendrogram provides a tree-like representation of how the data is partitioned into clusters, revealing the relationships and distances between data points.

Additionally, we’ve indicated an important aspect of our clustering analysis by specifying ‘k=3’ when highlighting clusters in the dendrogram. This helps identify distinct groupings within the data, allowing us to focus on the most meaningful clusters.

hcd <- as.dendrogram(pfit)
plot(hcd, ylim=c(30,100), cex = 0.2, main="Dendogram Subset", xlab="Data Points", ylab="Height")
rect.hclust(pfit, k=3)
text(x = 60, y = 32, labels = "Cluster 1", col = "red", cex = 0.8)
text(x = 160, y = 32, labels = "Cluster 3", col = "red", cex = 0.5)
text(x = 600, y = 32, labels = "Cluster 2", col = "red", cex = 0.9)

Hierarchical clustering with Ward’s method has successfully grouped data points into clusters that minimize internal variability. The dendrogram visually illustrates the hierarchy of clusters, providing insights into how data points are related. The ‘k=3’ parameter narrows the focus to three significant clusters within the data. This suggests that our analysis has uncovered three distinct patterns or groups among the records.

In the clustering analysis, we’ve successfully partitioned our data into three distinct clusters using hierarchical clustering and Ward’s method. To further explore and analyze these clusters, we’ve extracted the data points associated with each cluster into separate data frames.

groups <- cutree(pfit, k=3)
store_clusters <- function(d, groups, cols_to_store) {
Ngroups <- max(groups)
cluster_dfs <- list()
for (i in 1:Ngroups) {
cluster_name <- paste0("cluster_", i)
cluster_dfs[[cluster_name]] <- d[groups == i, cols_to_store]

}
return(cluster_dfs)
}
cols_to_store <-  c("subscribers","video_views","uploads","country_rank","channel_type", "channel_type_rank","category", "highest_monthly_earnings","Country","Average_GDP_PCAP")
cluster_dfs <- store_clusters(d, groups, cols_to_store)

The store_clusters function accomplishes this task. It takes the original dataset, the cluster assignments (groups), and a list of columns to store as input. For each cluster, the function creates a new data frame that includes only the relevant columns from the original dataset. The resulting data frames are then organized into a list named cluster_dfs. For the specific columns we’re interested in, such as “subscribers,” “video_views,” “uploads,” and more, we store them for each cluster. The goal is to facilitate a detailed examination of the characteristics of each cluster and gain insights into what distinguishes one cluster from another.

# Extract the clusters from the cluster_dfs list into separate dataframes
cluster_1 <- cluster_dfs[["cluster_1"]]
cluster_2 <- cluster_dfs[["cluster_2"]]
cluster_3 <- cluster_dfs[["cluster_3"]]

Additionally, we extract these clustered data points from the cluster_dfs list into individual data frames, namely cluster_1, cluster_2, and cluster_3. This enables us to perform more in-depth analyses, visualizations, or further modeling specific to each cluster.

Cluster 1 Insights: Viral Channels

Cluster 1 stands out as an intriguing group within our dataset. Notably, it exhibits a diverse spread across different countries. However, a distinctive trend emerges - a lower number of video uploads accompanied by an exceptionally high number of views.

What’s fascinating about this cluster is the observation that despite having a relatively small number of uploads, some channels within this group have accumulated tens of billions of views. In many cases, this phenomenon is linked to just one or two videos that were uploaded and subsequently went viral. This unique characteristic could be likened to a collection of anomalies in our dataset.

cluster_1 <- cluster_1[cluster_1$uploads != 0,]

c1_uploads <- ggplot(cluster_1, aes(x = uploads)) +

Additionally, we’ve crafted a scatterplot that illustrates the relationship between the number of uploads and the corresponding number of views. These visualizations provide further insight into the intriguing dynamics of Cluster 1, revealing the stark contrast between the number of uploads and the extent of their impact in terms of viewership.

The juxtaposition of these visualizations paints a vivid picture of this unique cluster, shedding light on the exceptional channels that make up “Cluster 1: Viral Channels.”

Selecting k for Clustering

Choosing an appropriate number of clusters, represented by ‘k,’ is a crucial step in clustering analysis. We employed a series of statistical and graphical techniques to make this decision.

Initially, we engaged in some trial and error to develop an understanding of the underlying data and the intuition behind clustering. However, as the summary of the results indicates, the data appeared noisy, and further exploration was needed.

The stability of clusters was evaluated through a machine-intensive iterative process, which indicated that Cluster 1 and 2 were relatively stable, while Cluster 3 exhibited comparatively less stability. This evaluation was conducted for various k values, ranging from 2 to 8. Other cluster stability metrics were also assessed. While many clusters demonstrated stability, none consistently achieved a perfect score of 0.8 or higher.

summary(cboot.hclust$result)
##               Length Class  Mode     
## result          7    hclust list     
## noise           1    -none- logical  
## nc              1    -none- numeric  
## clusterlist     3    -none- list     
## partition     989    -none- numeric  
## clustermethod   1    -none- character
## nccl            1    -none- numeric

In pursuit of better interpretability and to avoid overcomplicating the analysis, we opted to select 3 clusters, a choice that has been previously justified.

(values <- 1 - cboot.hclust$bootbrd/100) 
## [1] 1.00 1.00 0.47

We also considered k-means clustering by utilizing the ‘kmeans’ library with the ‘hclustCBI’ parameter. The computational process included generating statistical scores for the Calinski-Harabasz Index (CH Index) and Average Silhouette Width (ASW).

kbest.p <- 3
kmClusters <- kmeans(scaled_df, kbest.p, nstart=100, iter.max=100)

The results from these computations revealed that k = 3 is the most suitable choice based on the ASW characteristic, as it offers the best balance between interpretability and data representation.

The statistical scores of CH Index and ASW have been calculated below.

library(fpc)
kmClustering.ch <- kmeansruns(scaled_df, krange=1:10, criterion="ch")
kmClustering.ch$bestk
## [1] 8
kmClustering.asw <- kmeansruns(scaled_df, krange=1:10, criterion="asw")
kmClustering.asw$bestk
## [1] 3

The chart below provides a visual representation of these statistics, illustrating the relationship between different values of k and the associated CH Index and ASW scores.

library(gridExtra)
kmCritframe <- data.frame(k=1:10, ch=kmClustering.ch$crit,
asw=kmClustering.asw$crit)
fig1 <- ggplot(kmCritframe, aes(x=k, y=ch)) +
geom_point() + geom_line(colour="red") +
scale_x_continuous(breaks=1:10, labels=1:10) +
labs(y="CH index") + theme(text=element_text(size=20))
fig2 <- ggplot(kmCritframe, aes(x=k, y=asw)) +
geom_point() + geom_line(colour="blue") +
scale_x_continuous(breaks=1:10, labels=1:10) +
labs(y="ASW") + theme(text=element_text(size=20))
grid.arrange(fig1, fig2, nrow=1)

Overall, this process allowed us to confidently determine the most appropriate number of clusters for our analysis, which was found to be 3.
